# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] The **field of fire** or **zone of fire** (**ZF**) of a weapon, or group of weapons, is the area around it that can easily and effectively be reached by projectiles from a given position.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] The term originally came from the *field of fire* in front of forts (and similar defensive positions), cleared so there was no shelter for an approaching enemy.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] A similar term **sector of fire** is used to describe the area into which each gunner or group are *allowed* to fire.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] The boundaries are assigned by the commanding officer and thus can be arbitrary, even three-dimensional (a rifleman attacking a building might be assigned a set of windows to target).
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] The **arc of fire** of a mounted gun is a horizontal ("traverse") angle range within which the gun (or guns) can be fired.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] It can be limited by the construction of the gun mount or obstacles (for example, superstructure of a ship).
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] If there are no restrictions, the term *all-round arc of fire* is sometimes used.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] Overlapping arcs of fire create a crossfire.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] The **cone of fire** describes a cone-like pattern formed by the projectiles with the gun not being moved.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] It is mostly used in reference to machine guns.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] The spread of rounds is due to vibration of the gun, tolerances of the ammunition and weapon, and the gunner's posture.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] For a typical machine gun, the spread between bullets is proportional to the distance (for example, the width of the cone for M240G is 2⁄1000 of the distance).
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] The cone of fire makes impact in an elliptical pattern called the **beaten zone**.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] When firing over terrain, any space up to 1.8 m above the ground (the height of an average man) is considered **danger space**; that is, within the effects of the rounds.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] For small arms fire, when the distance to the beaten zone is up to approximately 700 m, on a flat terrain the danger zone is contiguous (the trajectory of the round is never above the height of a man).
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] The area that cannot be seen or aimed at within the gun's range (usually due to the terrain) is referred to as dead space.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/arc-of-fire] It is sometimes possible to send projectiles into the dead space using the indirect fire.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The **Musée de l'Armée** (French: [myze də laʁme]; "Army Museum") is a national military museum of France located at Les Invalides in the 7th arrondissement of Paris.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The Musée de l'Armée was created in 1905 with the merger of the Musée d'Artillerie and the Musée Historique de l'Armée.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The museum's seven main spaces and departments contain collections that span the period from antiquity through the 20th century.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The *Musée de l'artillerie* (Museum of Artillery – "*artillerie*" meaning all things related to weapons) was founded in 1795 in the aftermath of the French Revolution, and expanded under Napoleon.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] It was moved into the Hôtel des Invalides in 1871, immediately following the Franco-Prussian War and the proclamation of the Third Republic.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] Another institution called the *Musée historique de l'Armée* (Historical Museum of the Army) was created in 1896 following the Paris World Fair.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The two institutions merged in 1905 within the space of the former *Musée de l'Artillerie*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] Today, it holds 500,000 artifacts, including weapons, armour, artillery, uniforms, emblems and paintings, exhibited in an area of 12,000 m2.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The permanent collections are organised into "historical collections", representing a chronological tour from ancient times through the end of World War II.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] In March 1878, the museum hosted an "ethnographic exhibition", as it was called, which represented the main "types" of Oceania, America, Asia and Africa.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] Dummies representing people from the colonies, along with weapons and equipment, were the main attraction.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The exhibit, organised by Colonel Le Clerc, attempted to demonstrate theories of unilineal evolution, putting the European man at the apex of human history.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] Parts of this collection began to be transferred to the Ethnographic Museum of the Trocadéro in 1910 and in 1917; the last colonial rooms were closed just after the 1931 Paris Colonial Exhibition.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] All remnants were transferred after the Second World War.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The Musée de l'Armée has identified 24 aesthetic, technical and symbolic "treasures," which are all closely linked to French military history from the late Middle Ages through to World War II.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] They include weapons, armour, works of arts and technology.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The Main Courtyard is the centre of the Hôtel National des Invalides and displays a large part of the artillery collections, gathered during the French Revolution.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The collection traces 200 years of the history of French field artillery and enables visitors to discover how the equipment was manufactured, its role and the history of great French artillerymen.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The Musée de l'Armée has a rich ancient collection, which makes it one of the three largest arms museums in the world.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] This department covers the military, political, social and industrial history of France, reliving great battles, exploring the lives of soldiers, and tracing the development of technologies and tactics.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The contemporary department tells the story of the French Army from 1871 to 1945, and the two great conflicts of the 20th century.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The Charles de Gaulle Monument (*Historial*) is an interactive multimedia space dedicated to the work of Charles de Gaulle, the leader of the Free French Forces and founding President of the Fifth Republic.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] Three cabinets are dedicated to special collections.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The museum is dedicated to the Ordre de la Libération, France's second national order after the Légion d'honneur, which was created in 1940 by General Charles de Gaulle, leader of the Free French Forces.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The *Musée des Plans-Reliefs* is a museum of military models located within the Musée de l'Armée.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] About 100 models, created between 1668 and 1870, are currently on display in the museum.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The construction of models dates to 1668 when the Marquis de Louvois, minister of war to Louis XIV, began a collection of three-dimensional models of fortified cities for military purposes, and kept growing until 1870 with the disappearance of *fortifications bastionnées*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] In 1676, the Secretary of State for War, Marquis de Louvois, entrusted the young architect Jules Hardouin-Mansart with the construction of the chapel, which Libéral Bruant had been unable to complete.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The architect designed a building which combined a royal chapel, the "Dôme des Invalides", and a veterans' chapel.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] This way, the King and his soldiers could attend mass simultaneously, while entering the place of worship though different entrances, as prescribed by etiquette.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] This separation was reinforced in the 19th century with the erection of the tomb of Napoleon I, the creation of the two separate altars and then with the construction of a glass wall between the two chapels.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/army-museum-paris] The Dôme des Invalides is the emblem of the Hôtel National des Invalides and an unmissable monument in the Parisian landscape.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/ballistic-table] Ballistic tables commonly are used in target shooting, hunting, military sharpshooting and ballistic science applications.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/ballistic-table] After ranging the intended target, the shooter can then read off the chart data to estimate the ballistic correction required (relative to a zeroed range) and calibrate the aim accordingly by turning the adjustment knobs on the scope and/or using the reference markings on the scope's reticle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/ballistic-table] Ballistic tables are usually generated using specifically designed computer programs built on mathematical functions known as **ballistic softwares**, and an electronic device that runs ballistic softwares is called a **ballistic calculator** or **ballistic computer**.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/ballistic-table] The number of inputs to the ballistic calculator can sometimes vary depended on the specific generator, or the user may choose to only input certain variables.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/ballistic-table] For example, a very simple drop table can be made using inputs for the sight adjustment value (in mil or MOA), the zero range, intended target ranges, muzzle velocity, caliber, ballistic coefficient and bullet weight.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/ballistic-table] Some of the environmental effects that play a role in calculating the trajectory are gravity, projectile spin, wind, temperature, air pressure and humidity.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/ballistic-table] More advanced tables can take more factors into account to ensure a more accurate prediction of the trajectory, which becomes increasingly affected by gravity and wind drift over longer distances due to the more prolonged bullet flight.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/ballistic-table] Some of these variables may have a negligible effect on shorter ranges.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The **Battle of Hampton Roads**, also referred to as the **Battle of the *Monitor* and *Merrimack*** or the **Battle of Ironclads**, was a naval battle during the American Civil War.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle was fought over two days, March 8 and 9, 1862, in Hampton Roads, a roadstead in Virginia where the Elizabeth and Nansemond rivers meet the James River just before it flows into Chesapeake Bay by the city of Norfolk.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle was a part of the effort of the Confederacy to break the Union blockade, which had cut off Virginia's largest cities and major industrial centers, Norfolk and Richmond, from international trade.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] This battle was significant in that it was the first combat between ironclad warships, the USS *Monitor* and CSS *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Confederate fleet consisted of the ironclad ram *Virginia* (built from remnants of the burned steam frigate USS *Merrimack*) and several supporting vessels.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the first day of battle, they were opposed by several conventional, wooden-hulled ships of the Union Navy.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On that day, the *Virginia* was able to destroy two ships of the Union flotilla, USS *Congress* and USS *Cumberland*, and was about to attack a third, USS *Minnesota*, which had run aground.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, the action was halted by darkness and falling tide, so *Virginia* retired to take care of her few wounded—which included her captain, Flag Officer Franklin Buchanan—and repair her minimal battle damage.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Determined to complete the destruction of *Minnesota*, Catesby ap Roger Jones, acting as captain in Buchanan's absence, returned the ship to the fray the next morning, March 9.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the night, however, the ironclad *Monitor* had arrived and had taken a position to defend *Minnesota*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When *Virginia* approached, *Monitor* intercepted her.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The two ironclads fought for about three hours, with neither able to inflict significant damage on the other.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The duel ended indecisively, *Virginia* returning to her home at the Gosport Navy Yard for repairs and strengthening, and *Monitor* to her station defending *Minnesota*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The ships did not fight again, and the blockade remained in place.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle received worldwide attention, having immediate effects on navies around the world.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The preeminent naval powers, Great Britain and France, halted further construction of wooden-hulled ships, and others followed suit.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although Britain and France had been engaged in an iron-clad arms race since the 1830s, the Battle of Hampton Roads signaled a new age of naval warfare had arrived for the whole world.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] A new type of warship, monitor, was produced on the principle of the original.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The use of a small number of very heavy guns, mounted so that they could fire in all directions, was first demonstrated by *Monitor* but soon became standard in warships of all types.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Shipbuilders also incorporated rams into the designs of warship hulls for the rest of the century.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On April 19, 1861, shortly after the outbreak of hostilities at Charleston Harbor, US President Abraham Lincoln proclaimed a blockade of ports in the seceded states.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On April 27, after Virginia and North Carolina had also passed ordinances of secession, the blockade was extended to include their ports also.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Even before the extension, local troops had seized the Norfolk area and threatened the Gosport Navy Yard in Portsmouth.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The commandant there, Captain Charles S.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] McCauley, though loyal to the Union, was immobilized by advice he received from his subordinate officers, most of whom were in favor of secession.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although he had orders from (Union) Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles to move his ships to Northern ports, he refused to act until April 20, when he gave orders to scuttle the ships in the yard and destroy its facilities.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At least nine ships were burned, among them the screw frigate USS *Merrimack*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Merrimack* burned only to the waterline, however, and her engines were more or less intact.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The destruction of the navy yard was mostly ineffective; in particular, the large drydock there was relatively undamaged and soon could be restored.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Without firing a shot, the advocates of secession had gained for the South its largest navy yard, as well as the hull and engines of what would be in time its most famous warship.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] They had also seized more than a thousand heavy guns, plus gun carriages and large quantities of gunpowder.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] With Norfolk and its navy yard in Portsmouth, the Confederacy controlled the southern side of Hampton Roads.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] To prevent Union warships from attacking the yard, the Confederates set up batteries at Sewell's Point and Craney Island, at the juncture of the Elizabeth River with the James.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] (See map.) The Union retained possession of Fort Monroe, at Old Point Comfort on the Virginia Peninsula.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] They also held a small man-made island known as the Rip Raps, on the far side of the channel opposite Fort Monroe, and on this island they completed another fort, named Fort Wool.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] With Fort Monroe went control of the lower Peninsula as far as Newport News.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Forts Monroe and Wool gave the Union forces control of the entrance to Hampton Roads.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The blockade, initiated on April 30, 1861, cut off Norfolk and Richmond from the sea almost completely.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] To further the blockade, the Union Navy stationed some of its most powerful warships in the roadstead.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] There, they were under the shelter of the shore-based guns of Fort Monroe and the batteries at Hampton and Newport News and out of the range of the guns at Sewell's Point and Craney Island.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] For most of the first year of the war, the Confederacy could do little to oppose or dislodge them.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When steam propulsion began to be applied to warships, naval constructors renewed their interest in armor for their vessels.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Experiments had been tried with armor during the Crimean War (1853–1856), just prior to the American Civil War, and the British and French navies had each built armored ships and were planning to build others.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In 1860 the French Navy commissioned *La Gloire*, the world's first ocean-going ironclad warship.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Great Britain followed a year later with HMS *Warrior*, the world's first armor-plated iron-hulled warship.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The use of armor remained controversial, however, and the United States Navy was generally reluctant to embrace the new technology.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When the Civil War broke out in 1861, Confederate Secretary of the Navy Stephen R.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory was an early enthusiast for the advantages of armor.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As he looked upon it, the Confederacy could not match the industrial North in numbers of ships at sea, so they would have to compete by building vessels that individually outclassed those of the Union.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory gathered about himself a group of men who could put his vision into practice, among them John M.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When Mallory's men searched the South for factories that could build engines to drive the heavy ships that he wanted, they found no place to do it immediately.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At the best facility, the Tredegar Iron Works in Richmond, building engines from scratch would take at least a year.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Upon learning this, Williamson suggested taking the engines from the hulk of *Merrimack*, recently raised from the bed of the Elizabeth River.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] His colleagues promptly accepted his suggestion and expanded it, proposing that the design of their projected ironclad be adapted to the hull.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Porter produced the revised plans, which were submitted to Mallory for approval.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On July 11, 1861, the new design was accepted, and work began almost immediately.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The burned-out hull was towed into the graving dock that the Union Navy had failed to destroy.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the subsequent conversion process, the plans developed further, incorporating an iron ram fitted to the prow.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The re-modeled ship's offense, in addition to the ram, consisted of 10 guns: six 9 in (230 mm) smooth-bore Dahlgrens, two 6.4 in (160 mm) and two 7 in (180 mm) Brooke rifles.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Trials showed that these rifles firing solid shot would pierce up to eight inches of armor plating.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Tredegar Iron works could produce both solid shot and shell, and since it was believed that *Virginia* would face only wooden ships, she was given only the explosive shell.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor plating, originally meant to be 1 in (25 mm) thick, was replaced by double plates, each 2 in (51 mm) thick, backed by 24 in (61 cm) of iron and pine.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor was pierced for 14 gunports: four on each broadside, three forward, and three aft.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The revisions, together with the usual problems associated with the transportation system of the South, resulted in delays that pushed out the launch date until February 3, 1862, and she was not commissioned until February 17, bearing the name CSS *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Intelligence that the Confederates were working to develop an ironclad caused consternation for the Union, but Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles waited for Congress to meet to request permission to consider building armored vessels; Congress gave this permission on August 3, 1861.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Welles appointed a commission, which became known as the Ironclad Board, of three senior naval officers to choose among the designs that were submitted for consideration.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The three men were Captains Joseph Smith, Hiram Paulding, and Commander Charles Henry Davis.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The board considered seventeen designs, and chose to support three.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first of the three to be completed, even though she was by far the most radical in design, was Swedish engineer and inventor John Ericsson's USS *Monitor*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ericsson's *Monitor*, which was built at Ericsson's yard on the East River in Greenpoint, Brooklyn, incorporated new and striking design features, the most significant of which were her armor and armament.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Instead of the large numbers of guns of rather small bore that had characterized warships in the past, Ericsson opted for only two guns of large caliber; he wanted to use 15 in (380 mm) guns, but had to settle for 11 in (280 mm) Dahlgren guns when the larger size were unavailable.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] These were mounted in a cylindrical turret, 20 ft (6.1 m) in diameter, 9 ft (2.7 m) high, covered with iron 8 in (200 mm) thick.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The whole rotated on a central spindle, and was moved by a steam engine that could be controlled by one man.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ericsson was afraid that using the full 30 pounds of black powder to fire the huge cannon would raise the risk of an explosion in the turret.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] He demanded that a charge of 15 pounds be used to lessen this possibility.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As with *Virginia*, trials found that a full charge would pierce armor plate, a finding that would have affected the outcome of the battle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] A serious flaw in the design was the pilot house from which the ship would be conned, a small structure forward of the turret on the main deck.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Its presence meant that the guns could not fire directly forward, and it was isolated from other activities on the ship.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the late start and the novelty of construction, *Monitor* was actually completed a few days before her counterpart *Virginia*, but the Confederates activated *Virginia* first.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Confederate chain of command was anomalous.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lieutenant Catesby ap Roger Jones had directed much of the conversion of *Merrimack* to *Virginia*, and he was disappointed when he was not named her captain.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Jones was retained aboard *Virginia*, but only as her executive officer.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ordinarily, the ship would have been led by a captain of the Confederate States Navy, to be determined by the rigid seniority system that was in place.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Secretary Mallory wanted the aggressive Franklin Buchanan, but at least two other captains had greater seniority and had applied for the post.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory evaded the issue by appointing Buchanan, head of the Office of Orders and Detail, flag officer in charge of the defenses of Norfolk and the James River.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As such, he could control the movements of *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Technically, therefore, the ship went into the battle without a captain.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the Union side, command of the North Atlantic Blockading Squadron was held by Flag Officer Louis M.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] He had devised a plan for his frigates to engage *Virginia*, hoping to trap her in their crossfire.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In the event, his plan broke down completely when four of the ships ran aground (one of them intentionally) in the confined waters of the roadstead.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the day of battle, Goldsborough was absent with the ships cooperating with the Burnside Expedition in North Carolina.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In his absence, leadership fell to his second in command, Captain John Marston of USS *Roanoke*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As *Roanoke* was one of the ships that ran aground, Marston was unable to materially influence the battle, and his participation is often disregarded.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Most accounts emphasize the contribution of the captain of *Monitor*, John L.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Marston did, however, disregard orders from Secretary of War Gideon Welles to send the *Monitor* back to Washington, D.C., ahead of the battle, ensuring that it would be present to confront the *Merrimack*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle began when the large and unwieldy CSS *Virginia* steamed into Hampton Roads on the morning of March 8, 1862.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Buchanan intended to attack as soon as possible.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* was accompanied from her moorings on the Elizabeth River by *Raleigh* and *Beaufort*, and was joined at Hampton Roads by the James River Squadron, *Patrick Henry*, *Jamestown*, and *Teaser*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When they were passing the Union batteries at Newport News, *Patrick Henry* was temporarily disabled by a shot in her boiler that killed four of her crew.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] After repairs, she returned and rejoined the others.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At this time, the Union Navy had five warships in the roadstead, in addition to several support vessels.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The sloop-of-war *Cumberland* and frigate *Congress* were anchored in the channel near Newport News.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lawrence* and the steam frigates *Roanoke* and *Minnesota* were near Fort Monroe, along with the storeship *Brandywine*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The latter three got under way as soon as they saw *Virginia* approaching, but all soon ran aground.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lawrence* and *Roanoke* took no further important part in the battle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ramming *Cumberland* nearly resulted in the sinking of *Virginia* as well.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia*'s bow ram got stuck in the enemy ship's hull, and as *Cumberland* listed and began to go down, she almost pulled *Virginia* under with her.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At the time the vessels were locked, one of *Cumberland's* anchors was hanging directly above the foredeck of *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Had it come loose, the two ships might have gone down together.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* broke free, however, her ram breaking off as she backed away.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Buchanan next turned *Virginia* on *Congress*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Seeing what had happened to *Cumberland*, Lieutenant Joseph B.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Smith, captain of *Congress*, ordered his ship grounded in shallow water.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] By this time, the James River Squadron, commanded by John Randolph Tucker, had arrived and joined *Virginia* in the attack on *Congress*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] After an hour of unequal combat, the badly damaged *Congress* surrendered.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] While the surviving crewmen of *Congress* were being ferried off the ship, a Union battery on the north shore opened fire on *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In retaliation, Buchanan ordered *Congress* fired upon with hot shot, cannonballs heated red-hot.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Congress* caught fire and burned throughout the rest of the day.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Near midnight, the flames reached her magazine and she exploded and sank, stern first.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Personnel losses included 110 killed or missing and presumed drowned.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Another 26 were wounded, of whom ten died within days.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although she had not suffered anything like the damage she had inflicted, *Virginia* was not completely unscathed.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Shots from *Cumberland*, *Congress*, and Union troops ashore had riddled her smokestack, reducing her already low speed.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Two of her guns were disabled and several armor plates had been loosened.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Two of her crew were killed, and more were wounded.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] One of the wounded was Captain Buchanan, who stood out into the open top of the *Virginia*, thinking it was perfectly safe, which led to him having his left thigh pierced by a rifle shot.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Meanwhile, the James River Squadron had turned its attention to *Minnesota*, which had left Fort Monroe to join in the battle and had run aground.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] After *Virginia* had dealt with the surrender of *Congress*, she joined the James River Squadron despite her damage.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because of her deep draft and the falling tide, however, *Virginia* was unable to get close enough to be effective, and darkness prevented the rest of the squadron from aiming their guns to any effect.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* left with the expectation of returning the next day and completing the task.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She retreated into the safety of Confederate-controlled waters off Sewell's Point for the night, but had killed 250 enemy sailors and had lost two.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Union had lost two ships and three were aground.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The United States Navy's greatest defeat (which would remain so until World War II) caused panic in Washington.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As Lincoln's Cabinet met to discuss the disaster, the frightened Secretary of War Edwin Stanton told the others that *Virginia* might attack East coast cities, and even shell the White House before the meeting ended.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Welles assured his colleagues that they were safe as the ship could not traverse the Potomac River.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] He added that the Union also had an ironclad, and that it was heading to meet *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both sides used the respite to prepare for the next day.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* put her wounded ashore and underwent temporary repairs.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Buchanan was among the wounded, so command on the second day fell to his executive officer, Lieutenant Catesby ap Roger Jones.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Jones proved to be no less aggressive than the man he replaced.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] While *Virginia* was being prepared for renewal of the battle, and while *Congress* was still ablaze, *Monitor*, commanded by Lieutenant John L.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Union ironclad had been rushed to Hampton Roads in hopes of protecting the Union fleet and preventing *Virginia* from threatening Union cities.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Worden was informed that his primary task was to protect *Minnesota*, so *Monitor* took up a position near the grounded *Minnesota* and waited.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] "All on board felt we had a friend that would stand by us in our hour of trial," wrote Captain Gershom Jacques Van Brunt, *Minnesota*'s commander, in his official report the day after the engagement.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The next morning, at dawn on March 9, 1862, *Virginia* left her anchorage at Sewell's Point and moved to attack *Minnesota*, still aground.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was followed by the three ships of the James River Squadron.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] They found their course blocked, however, by the newly arrived *Monitor*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At first, Jones believed the strange craft—which one Confederate sailor mocked as "a cheese on a raft"—to be a boiler being towed from the *Minnesota*, not realizing the nature of his opponent.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Soon, however, it was apparent that he had no choice but to fight her.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first shot of the engagement was fired at *Monitor* by *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The shot flew past *Monitor* and struck *Minnesota*, which answered with a broadside; this began what would be a lengthy engagement.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] "Again, all hands were called to quarters, and when she approached within a mile of us I opened upon her with my stern guns and made a signal to the *Monitor* to attack the enemy," Van Brunt added.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] After fighting for hours, mostly at close range, neither could overcome the other.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor of both ships proved adequate.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In part, this was because each was handicapped in her offensive capabilities.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Buchanan, in *Virginia*, had not expected to fight another armored vessel, so his guns were supplied only with shell rather than armor-piercing shot.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Monitor*'s guns were used with the standard service charge of only 15 lb (6.8 kg) of powder, which did not give the projectile sufficient momentum to penetrate her opponent's armor.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Tests conducted after the battle showed that the Dahlgren guns could be operated safely and efficiently with charges of as much as 30 lb (14 kg).
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, despite this, as the two ironclads circled each other during the fight, *Monitor* was about to penetrate *Virginia'*s armor, but a misfiring of her weapons caused her to lose the advantage.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At 10 AM that morning, *Virginia* grounded.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Monitor* opened fire on her vulnerable adversary, yet *Virginia* was able to scrape off the shore and rejoin the fight.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Later during the battle, Acting Master Louis N.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder and officers Stimers and Truscott were inside the gun turret, discussing the course of action.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder was leaning against the turret's inside wall when it took a direct hit.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder was knocked unconscious and taken below, where it took him an hour to regain consciousness.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stodder thus became the first man injured during the battle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle finally ceased when a shell from *Virginia* struck the pilot house of *Monitor* and exploded, driving fragments of paint and iron through the viewing slits into Worden's eyes and temporarily blinding him.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As no one else could see to command the ship, *Monitor* was forced to draw off.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The executive officer, Lieutenant Samuel Dana Greene, took over, and *Monitor* returned to the fight.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In the period of command confusion, however, the crew of *Virginia* believed that their opponent had withdrawn.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although *Minnesota* was still aground, the falling tide meant that she was out of reach.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Furthermore, *Virginia* had suffered enough damage to require extensive repair.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Convinced that his ship had won the day, Jones ordered her back to Norfolk.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] At about this time, *Monitor* returned, only to discover her opponent apparently giving up the fight.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Convinced that *Virginia* was quitting, with orders only to protect *Minnesota* and not to risk his ship unnecessarily, Greene did not pursue.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Thus, each side misinterpreted the moves of the other, and as a result each claimed victory.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the two-day engagement, USS *Minnesota* shot off 78 rounds of 10-inch solid shot; 67 rounds of 10-inch shells with 15-second fuse; 169 rounds of 9-inch solid shot; 180 9-inch shells with 15-second fuse; 35 8-inch shells with 15-second fuse and 5,567.5 pounds of service powder.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Three crew members, Alexander Winslow, Henry Smith and Dennis Harrington were killed during the battle and 16 were wounded.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] One of *Monitor*'s crew, Quartermaster Peter Williams, was awarded the Medal of Honor for his actions during the battle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] By late March, the Union blockade fleet had been augmented by hastily refitted civilian ships, including the powerful SS *Vanderbilt*, SS *Arago*, SS *Illinois*, and SS *Ericsson*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] These had been outfitted with rams and some iron plating.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] By late April, the new ironclads USRC *E.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Stevens* and USS *Galena* had also joined the blockade.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Each side considered how best to eliminate the threat posed by its opponent, and after *Virginia* returned each side tried to goad the other into attacking under unfavorable circumstances.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both captains declined the opportunity to fight in waters not of their own choosing; Jeffers in particular was under positive orders not to risk his ship.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Consequently, each vessel spent the next month in what amounted to posturing.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because the blockade was unbroken, Norfolk was of little strategic use to the Confederacy, and preliminary plans were laid to move the ship up the James River to the vicinity of Richmond.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Before adequate preparations could be made, the Confederate Army under Major General Benjamin Huger abandoned the city on May 9, without consulting anyone from the Navy.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia*'s draft was too great to permit her to pass up the river, which had a depth of only 18 ft (5.5 m), and then only under favorable circumstances.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was trapped and could only be captured or sunk by the Union Navy.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Rather than allow either, Tattnall decided to destroy his own ship.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] He had her towed down to Craney Island in Portsmouth, where the gang were taken ashore, and then she was set afire.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She burned through the rest of the day and most of the following night; shortly before dawn, the flames reached her magazine, and she blew up.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The victory claims that were made by both sides in the immediate aftermath of the Battle of Hampton Roads were based on misinterpretations of the opponent's behavior and have been dismissed by present-day historians.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] They agree that the result of the *Monitor*–*Virginia* encounter was not a victory for either side.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] As the combat between ironclads was the primary significance of the battle, the general verdict is that the overall result was a draw.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] All would acknowledge that the Southern fleet inflicted far more damage than it received, which would ordinarily imply that they had gained a tactical victory.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Compared to other Civil War battles, the loss of men and ships for the Union Navy would be considered a clear defeat.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the other hand, the blockade was not seriously threatened, so the entire battle can be regarded as an assault that ultimately failed.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, initially after the Battle of Hampton Roads, both the Confederate and Union media claimed victory for their own sides.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] A headline in a Boston newspaper the day after the battle read "The Merrimac Driven back by the Steamer!", implying a Union victory, while Confederate media focused on their original success against wooden Union ships.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the battle ending in a stalemate, it was seen by both sides as an opportunity to raise war-time morale, especially since the ironclad ships were an exciting naval innovation that intrigued citizens.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Evaluation of the strategic results is likewise disputed.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The blockade was maintained, even strengthened, and *Virginia* was bottled up in Hampton Roads.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because a decisive Confederate weapon was negated, some have concluded that the Union could claim a strategic victory.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Confederate advocates can counter, however, by arguing that *Virginia* had a military significance larger than the blockade, which was only a small part of the war in Tidewater Virginia.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Her mere presence was sufficient to close the James River to Federal incursions.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She also imposed other constraints on the Peninsula Campaign then being mounted by the Union Army under General George B.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] McClellan, who worried that she could interfere with his positions on the York River.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although his fears were baseless, they continued to affect the movements of his army until *Virginia* was destroyed.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both days of the battle attracted attention from almost all the world's navies.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] USS *Monitor* became the prototype for the monitor warship type.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She thus became the first of two ships whose names were applied to entire classes of their successors, the other being HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Many more were built, including river monitors, and they played key roles in Civil War battles on the Mississippi and James rivers.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The US immediately started the construction of ten more monitors based on Ericsson's original larger plan, known as the *Passaic*-class monitors.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] More than 20 additional monitors were built by the Union by the end of the war.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, while the design proved exceptionally well-suited for river combat, the low profile and heavy turret caused poor seaworthiness in rough waters.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Russia, fearing that the American Civil War would spill into Russian Alaska, launched ten sister ships, as soon as Ericsson's plans reached St.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] What followed has been described as *"Monitor mania"*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The revolving turret later inspired similar designs for future warships, which eventually became the modern battleship.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The vulnerability of wooden hulls to armored ships was noted particularly in Britain and France, where the wisdom of the planned conversion of the battle fleet to armor was given a powerful demonstration.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Another feature that was emulated was not so successful.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Impressed by the ease with which *Virginia* had sunk *Cumberland*, naval architects began to incorporate rams into their hull designs.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first purpose-built ram in the modern era was the French armored ram *Taureau*, whose guns were said to have "the sole function of preparing the way for the ram." The inclusion of rams in warship hull design persisted almost to the outbreak of World War I.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The name of the warship that served the Confederacy in the Battle of Hampton Roads has been a continuing source of confusion and some contention.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was originally a screw frigate in the United States Navy carrying the name USS *Merrimack*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] All parties continued to use the name after her capture by secessionists while she was being rebuilt as an ironclad.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] When her conversion was almost complete, her name was officially changed to *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the official name change, Union accounts persisted in calling *Merrimack* by her original name, while Confederate sources used either *Virginia* or *Merrimac(k)*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The alliteration of *Monitor* and *Merrimack* has persuaded most popular accounts to adopt the familiar name, even when it is acknowledged to be technically incorrect.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was a paddle wheel steamer named for the victor (as most Southerners saw it) at Hampton Roads.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] She was used for running the blockade until she was captured and taken into Federal service, still named *Merrimac.* Her name was a spelling variant of the river, namesake of USS *Merrimack*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both spellings are still in use around the Hampton Roads area.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] A small community in Montgomery County, Virginia, near the location where the iron for the Confederate ironclad was forged is now known as Merrimac.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Some of the iron mined there and used in the plating on the Confederate ironclad is displayed at the Norfolk Naval Shipyard in Portsmouth.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The anchor of *Virginia* sits on the lawn in front of the American Civil War Museum in Richmond.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] After resting undetected on the ocean floor for 111 years, the wreck of *Monitor* was located by a team of scientists in 1973.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The remains of the ship were found upside down 16 mi (26 km) off Cape Hatteras, on a relatively flat, sandy bottom at a depth of about 240 ft (73 m).
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In 1987, the site was declared a National Marine Sanctuary, the first shipwreck to receive this distinction.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because of *Monitor*'s advanced state of deterioration, timely recovery of remaining significant artifacts and ship components became critical.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Numerous fragile artifacts, including the innovative turret and its two Dahlgren guns, an anchor, steam engine, and propeller, have been recovered.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] They were transported back to Hampton Roads to the Mariners' Museum in Newport News, Virginia, where they were treated in special tanks to stabilize the metal.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] It was reported that it would take about ten years for the metal to completely stabilize.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The new USS *Monitor* Center at the Mariners' Museum officially opened on March 9, 2007, and a full-scale copy of USS *Monitor*, the original recovered turret, and artifacts and related items are now on display.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Battle of Hampton Roads was a significant event in both Naval and Civil War history that has been detailed in many books, televised Civil War documentaries, and in film, to include TNT's 1991 *Ironclads*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In New York City, where the designer of the Monitor, John Ericsson, died in March 1889, a statue was commissioned by the state to commemorate the battle between the Ironclads.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The statue features a stylized male nude allegorical figure on water between two iron cleats.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] In Virginia, the state dedicated the Monitor-Merrimack Overlook at Anderson Park on a jetty that overlooks the site of the battle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] The park contains several historical markers commemorating both ships.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/battle-of-hampton-roads] Also, in 1992, Virginia dedicated the $400 million, 4.6-mile-long Monitor-Merrimac Memorial Bridge-Tunnel, which is located less than 1 mile from the site of the battle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] A **breechloader** is a firearm or artillery piece in which the user loads the ammunition from the breech (rear) end of the barrel.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The vast majority of modern firearms are breechloaders.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Before the mid-19th century, most guns were muzzleloaders, guns loaded from the muzzle (front) end of the barrel.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Only a few muzzle-loading weapons, such as mortars, rifle grenades, some rocket launchers, such as the Panzerfaust 3 and RPG-7, and the GP series grenade launchers, have remained in common usage in modern military conflicts.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] However, referring to a weapon explicitly as breech-loading is mostly limited to weapons in which the operator loads ammunition by hand (and not by operating a mechanism such as a bolt action), such as artillery pieces or break-action small arms.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Breech-loading designs provide several advantages, chief among which is reduced reload time.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Rather than having to push propellant and projectile through the whole length of the barrel and pack it down, they can be simply inserted into the chamber far quicker.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The reloading process itself is also streamlined, as the weapons do not need to be maneuvered around as much; for artillery, this also allows gun emplacements to be smaller and the crew to remain better protected.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Rifled or fouled barrels do not impede loading the breech.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Another advantage is that projectiles could be made to fit the bore tightly, increasing power, range and accuracy.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Unloading a breechloader is much easier as well, as the ammunition can be unloaded from the breech end, which can often be done by hand.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Unloading muzzleloaders requires drilling into the projectile to drag it out through the whole length of the barrel, and in some cases, the guns are simply fired to facilitate the unloading process.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The advent of breechloading gave a significant increase to effective firepower by its own right, and it also enabled further revolutions in firearm designs such as repeating and self-loading firearms.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Although breech-loading firearms were developed as far back as the early 14th century in Burgundy and various other parts of Europe, breech-loading became more successful with improvements in precision engineering and machining in the 19th century.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The main challenge for developers of breech-loading firearms was sealing the breech.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] That was eventually solved for smaller firearms by the development of the self-contained metallic cartridge in the mid-19th century.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] For firearms that are too large to use cartridges, the problem was solved by the development of the interrupted screw.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Breech-loading swivel guns were invented in the 14th century.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] They were a particular type of swivel gun, and consisted in a small breech-loading cannon equipped with a swivel for easy rotation, loaded by inserting a mug-shaped chamber already filled with powder and projectiles.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The breech-loading swivel gun had a high rate of fire, and was especially effective in anti-personnel roles.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Breech-loading firearms are known from the 16th century.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Henry VIII possessed one, which he apparently used as a hunting gun to shoot birds.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Meanwhile, in China, an early form of breech-loading musket, known as the Che Dian Chong, was known to have been created in the second half of the 16th century for the Ming dynasty's arsenals.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Like all early breech-loading fireams, gas leakage was a limitation and danger present in the weapon's mechanism.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] More breech-loading firearms were made in the early 18th century.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] One such gun known to have belonged to Philip V of Spain, and was manufactured circa 1715, probably in Madrid.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] It came with a ready-to load reusable cartridge.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Patrick Ferguson, a British Army officer, developed in 1772 the Ferguson rifle, a breech-loading flintlock firearm.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Roughly two hundred of the rifles were manufactured and used in the Battle of Brandywine, during the American Revolutionary War, but shortly after they were retired and replaced with the standard Brown Bess musket.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] From the late 18th century to early 19th century, and later on into the mid-19th century, there were attempts in Europe at an effective breech-loader.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] There were concentrated attempts at improved cartridges and methods of ignition.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The cartridge was loaded through the breech and fired with a needle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The needle-activated central-fire breech-loading gun would become a major feature of firearms thereafter.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The corresponding firearm was also developed by Pauly.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Pauly made an improved version, which was protected by a patent on 29 September 1812.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The United States Army adopted the first standard breech-loading rifle, the Hall rifle of 1819, in large quantities.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The Pauly cartridge was further improved by the French gunsmith Casimir Lefaucheux in 1828, by adding a pinfire primer, but Lefaucheux did not register his patent until 1835: a pinfire cartridge containing powder in a cardboard shell.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In 1842, the Norwegian Armed Forces adopted the breech-loading caplock, the Kammerlader, one of the first instances in which a modern army widely adopted a breech-loading rifle as its main infantry firearm.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In 1845, another Frenchman Louis-Nicolas Flobert invented, for indoor shooting, the first rimfire metallic cartridge, constituted by a bullet fit in a percussion cap.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Usually derived in the 6 mm and 9 mm calibres, it is since then called the Flobert cartridge but it does not contain any powder; the only propellant substance contained in the cartridge is the percussion cap itself.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In English-speaking countries the Flobert cartridge corresponds to the .22 BB and .22 CB ammunitions.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In 1846, yet another Frenchman, Benjamin Houllier, patented the first fully metallic cartridge containing powder in a metallic shell.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Houllier commercialised his weapons in association with the gunsmiths Blanchard or Charles Robert.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] But the subsequent Houllier and Lefaucheux cartridges, even if they were the first full-metal shells, were still pinfire cartridges, like those used in the LeMat (1856) and Lefaucheux (1858) revolvers, although the LeMat also evolved in a revolver using rimfire cartridges.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The *Dreyse Zündnadelgewehr* (Dreyse needle gun) was a single-shot breech-loading rifle using a rotating bolt to seal the breech.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] It was so called because of its .5-inch needle-like firing pin, which passed through a paper cartridge case to impact a percussion cap at the bullet base.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] It began development in the 1830s under Johann Nicolaus von Dreyse and eventually an improved version of it was adopted by Prussia in the late 1840s.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The paper cartridge and the gun had numerous deficiencies; specifically, serious problems with gas leaking.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] However, the rifle was used to great success in the Prussian army in the Austro-Prussian War of 1866.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] This, and the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–71, eventually caused much interest in Europe for breech-loaders and the Prussian military system in general.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The first centrefire cartridge was introduced in 1855 by Pottet, with both Berdan and Boxer priming.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In 1860, the New Zealand government petitioned the Colonial Office for more soldiers to defend Auckland.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The bid was unsuccessful and the government began instead making inquiries to Britain to obtain modern weapons.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In 1861 they placed orders for the Calisher and Terry carbine, which used a breech-loading system using a bullet consisting of a standard Minié lead bullet in .54 calibre backed by a charge and tallowed wad, wrapped in nitrated paper to keep it waterproof.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The carbine had been issued in small numbers to English cavalry (Hussars) from 1857.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] About 3–4,000 carbines were brought into New Zealand a few years later.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The carbine was used extensively by the Forest Rangers, an irregular force led by Gustavus von Tempsky that specialized in bush warfare and reconnaissance.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Von Tempsky liked the short carbine, which could be loaded while lying down.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The waterproofed cartridge was easier to keep dry in the New Zealand bush.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Museums in New Zealand hold a small number of these carbines in good condition.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] During the American Civil War, at least nineteen types of breech-loaders were fielded.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The Sharps used a successful dropping block design.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The Greene used rotating bolt-action, and was fed from the breech.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The Spencer, which used lever-actuated bolt-action, was fed from a seven-round detachable tube magazine.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The Henry and Volcanic used rimfire metallic cartridges fed from a tube magazine under the barrel.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] These held a significant advantage over muzzle-loaders.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The improvements in breech-loaders had spelled the end of muzzle-loaders.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] To make use of the enormous number of war surplus muzzle-loaders, the Allin conversion Springfield was adopted in 1866.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] General Burnside invented a breech-loading rifle before the war, the Burnside carbine.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The French adopted the new Chassepot rifle in 1866, which was much improved over the Dreyse needle gun as it had dramatically fewer gas leaks due to its de Bange sealing system.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The British initially took the existing Enfield and fitted it with a Snider breech action (solid block, hinged parallel to the barrel) firing the Boxer cartridge.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Following a competitive examination of 104 guns in 1866, the British decided to adopt the Peabody-derived Martini-Henry with trap-door loading in 1871.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Single-shot breech-loaders would be used throughout the latter half of the 19th Century, but were slowly replaced by various designs for repeating rifles, first used in the American Civil War.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Manual breech-loaders gave way to manual magazine feed and then to self-loading rifles.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The first modern breech-loading rifled gun is a breech-loader invented by Martin von Wahrendorff with a cylindrical breech plug secured by a horizontal wedge in 1837.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] In the 1850s and 1860s, Joseph Whitworth and William Armstrong invented improved breech-loading artillery, the 12-pounder Whitworth rifle and the Armstrong gun.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The M1867 naval guns produced in Imperial Russia at the Obukhov State Plant used Krupp technology.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] A breech action is the loading sequence of a breech loading naval gun or small arm.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The earliest breech actions were either three-shot break-open actions or a barrel tip-down, remove the plug and reload actions.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The later breech-loaders included the Ferguson rifle, which used a screw-in/screw out action to reload, and the Hall rifle, which tipped up at 30 degrees for loading.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] The better breech loaders, however, used percussion caps, including the Sharps rifle, using a falling block (or sliding block) action to reload.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] And then later on came the Dreyse needle gun that used a moving seal (bolt) to seal and expose the breech.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/breech-loading-weapon] Later on, however, the Mauser M71/84 rifle used self-contained metallic cartridges and used a rotating bolt to open and close the breech.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] The former municipality of Brielle also included the communities of Vierpolders and Zwartewaal.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] On 1 January 2023, the municipality of Brielle merged with Hellevoetsluis and Westvoorne into the new municipality of Voorne aan Zee.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] Brielle, New Jersey was named after Brielle by the Dutch colonists of New Jersey, originally New Netherland.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] Its name is derived from the Celtic word *brogilo* (meaning "closed area" or "hunting grounds").
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] The oldest writings about Brielle indicate that the current location is the "new" Brielle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] *Den ouden Briel* (Old Brill) must have been situated somewhere else on the Voorne-Putten Island.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] It grew into a town of prestige in the 14th century.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] In 1330, Gerard van Voorne, independent Lord of Voorne and Viscount of Zeeland, granted town rights to Brielle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] This gave the town governmental and jurisdictional powers and certain trading rights, such as the right to trade fish and collect port taxes.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] The town was for a long time the seat of the Lords of Voorne, until this fiefdom was added to the County of Holland in 1371.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] It had its own harbour and traded with the countries around the Baltic Sea.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] Brielle even had its own trading colony in Sweden.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] This event is still celebrated each year on April 1 and the night before (known as Chalk Night (kalknacht) when the town is defaced with chalk - and now also white paint).
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] In Dutch, "de bril" is the word for "the glasses," and closely rhymes with Den Briel; as does "Fles" which stands for the town of Vlissingen or Flushing, the next town to be captured by the Dutch rebels.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] After the capture of Brielle the Protestant rebels tortured and murdered the Catholic Martyrs of Gorkum and Brielle has become a pilgrimage location since then.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] In August 1585, Brielle was one of the three Dutch towns that became an English possession by the Treaty of Nonsuch when Queen Elizabeth I received it as security of payment for 5000 soldiers (led by the Earl of Leicester) and used by the Dutch in their struggle against the Spanish.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] The first English governor of Brielle was Thomas Cecil, 1st Earl of Exeter, succeeded by Edward Conway, 1st Viscount Conway who named his daughter Brilliana in honour of the town.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] English garrisons were stationed here and at Flushing.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] Edmund Sheffield, 3rd Baron Sheffield governed the town from 1598.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brielle] In 1617, these cities returned to the Netherlands.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] The **Brooke rifle** was a type of rifled, muzzle-loading naval and coast defense gun designed by John Mercer Brooke, an officer in the Confederate States Navy.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] They were produced by plants in Richmond, Virginia, and Selma, Alabama, between 1861 and 1865 during the American Civil War.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] They served afloat on Confederate ships and ashore in coast defense batteries operated by the Confederate States Army.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Brookes can be identified by the presence of at least one band of wrought iron at the breech and a rough-finished, tapering barrel.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] The barrels were made of cast iron for ease of manufacture, but one or more wrought iron bands was welded around the chamber to reinforce it against the high chamber pressure exerted when the gun fired.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Because no southern foundries had the capacity to wrap the rifles in a single band like the Parrott design, a series of smaller bands were used, each usually 2 inches (51 mm) thick and 6 inches (152 mm) wide.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] All of Brooke's rifles used the same seven-groove rifling with a right-hand twist.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Most of Brooke's guns had a Gomer-style powder chamber, shaped like a truncated cone with a hemispherical tip, but the 6.4-inch rifles had a simple hemispherical powder chamber.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] These weapons were manufactured at the Tredegar Iron Works (sometimes referred to as J.R.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Anderson & Co, after owner Joseph Reid Anderson) in Richmond, Virginia, and at Selma Naval Ordnance Works in Selma, Alabama.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Guns manufactured at Selma bear the foundry imprint "S", those from Tredegar "TF".
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] "R.N.O.W" may be found on some guns as they were bored and rifled by the Richmond Naval Ordnance Works in Richmond, Virginia after a fire in May 1863 temporarily crippled Tredegar's boring shop.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Brooke reported fourteen single-banded 6.4 in (163 mm) rifles were completed by 8 January 1863, although Tredegar records list only eleven as some were double-banded before being shipped.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Three were cast in 1861 with the remainder in 1862.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Two of the earliest were mounted on the broadside of the ironclad CSS *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Two were mounted fore and aft on pivot carriages aboard the ironclad gunboat CSS *Neuse*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Two others were mounted on the broadside of the ironclad CSS *Atlanta* and survive today in Willard Park of the Washington Navy Yard.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Double-banded rifles were produced from 28 October 1862 by direction of Stephen Mallory, Confederate Secretary of the Navy.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Twenty-four were cast by Tredegar between 1862 and 1864 while Selma cast twenty-seven, but only fifteen were shipped due to casting problems.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Five of the damaged gun blocks were rebored as 8-inch (203 mm) double-banded smoothbores.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Nine survivors exist, including four from CSS *Tennessee II* and one from CSS *Albemarle*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] The first seven single-banded 7-inch (178 mm) were bored and rifled from 9-inch (229 mm) Dahlgren gun blocks between July and December 1861.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Two of these were the front and rear pivot guns of the CSS *Virginia*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Tredegar made another nineteen to the Brooke pattern between 1862 and 1863 of which three survive.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Two of these are found at the Washington Navy Yard as trophies from CSS *Atlanta*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Selma cast fifty-four double-banded rifles in 1863 and 1864, but only shipped thirty-nine due to casting flaws.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Tredegar cast thirty-six between 1863 and 1865.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Eight survive, two from CSS *Tennessee II*, one in the Washington Navy Yard and the other in Selma.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Another, number S89, may be found at Fort Morgan State Historic Park.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] On September 29, 2015, an archeological team from the University of South Carolina recovered a 7-inch double-banded gun from the CSS *Pedee*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] S96, which was mounted at Fort Sidney Johnston on the Tombigbee River, is currently displayed in front of the city hall of Jackson, Alabama.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] An additional rifle, S95, sits on private property near the site of Fort Stonewall.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Three triple-banded rifles were cast by Tredegar in 1862.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] These were 15 inches (380 mm) longer than the other 7-inch rifles and were unique among Brooke guns in that they lacked cast trunnions.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Instead a separate trunnion strap was fitted around the breech.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] One was mounted on the CSS *Richmond* and another was sent to the harbor defenses of Charleston, South Carolina, where it remains as a trophy in Ft.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Tredegar cast four double-banded 8 in (203 mm) rifles in April and May 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] One was mounted in CSS *Virginia II* while another was sent to the batteries defending the James River.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] It was present, but lacked shells during the fighting at Dutch Gap Canal on 13 August and 22 October 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Shells were delivered on 27 October and 2 November 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Brooke designed a series of smoothbores that were produced in small numbers by the Selma and Tredegar foundries.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Selma re-bored five flawed 6.4-inch blanks as 8-inch double-banded guns, one of which (S26) survives mounted in a cemetery in Gainesville, Alabama.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Brooke's 1863 report to Secretary Mallory shows a plate of an unbanded 8-inch smoothbore, but nothing further is known of it.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Similar attempts to bore out flawed 7-inch gun blocks to 9-inch (229 mm) smoothbores were unsuccessful.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Seven 10-inch (254 mm) double-banded guns were cast by Selma and four by Tredegar in 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Two survive, one of which is a trophy from CSS *Columbia* in the Washington Navy Yard.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Selma cast twelve 11-inch double-banded smoothbores in 1864, although only eight were shipped.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] In 1863 and 1864 two 11-inch triple-banded guns were cast by Tredegar, but none are known to survive.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] Brooke's rifles fired both armor-piercing and explosive shells of his own design.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] The former were solid cylindrical projectiles with a blunt or flat nose to reduce the chance of a ricochet, and were often referred in contemporary accounts as "bolts".
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] The latter were hollow cylinders with rounded or pointed noses.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] They were filled with black powder with a fuse set to detonate a variable amount of time after being fired.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/brooke-rifle] His smoothbores used spherical solid shot for armored targets and hollow spherical explosive shells against unarmored targets.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The **Canon de 24 C modèle 1864** was a cast iron rifled breech loader built-up gun used by the French Navy and as coastal artillery.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The Dutch army used it for coastal defense as '24 cm ijzer'.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The first rifled gun of the French navy was the Canon de 16 cm modèle 1855.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It was followed by a series of 7 guns known as the modèle 1858–1860.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] These were 6 new or modified cannon ranging from 14 to 16 cm caliber and one modified 22 cm shell gun.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] They were hooped with steel bands and fired a cylindrical projectile of about twice the weight of the round bullet.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] During the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, both the Unionist smoothbore 280 mm Dahlgren guns and the Confederate 7 inch Brooke rifles proved unable to effectively deal with armored opponents.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The first designs of almost all the French modèle 1864 guns date from October and December 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The family of modèle 1864 guns consisted of guns of five calibers: 14, 16, 19, 24, and 27 cm.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Obviously, the first measure to increase the punch, was to increase the caliber.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] However, the 1864 model also raised the average weight of the shot from two to three times the weight of the round shot.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Finally, a third measure was to increase the charge.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This way, the heavier shot still attained a higher velocity.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] As increasing the charge and increasing the weight of the projectile leads to higher peak pressures inside the gun, this can only be done by producing a more resilient barrel.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The first 24 cm modèle 1864 gun was designed in October 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] However, changes to the design continued to be made right up to January 1868.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This probably explains the designation 'modèle 1864-1866' for the family of guns designed in 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In a June 1866 session of the French Parliament, Henri Dupuy de Lôme gave some details about the rifled modèle 1864 guns that were being developed.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] He first stated the weight of the 16 and 19 cm guns and that of the projectiles they used.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Dupuy de Lôme then said that the 24 cm gun was the heaviest piece intended for use on board, and that it weighed 14,000 kg.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] His statements about the projectiles that the 24 cm gun used were in the future tense.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The gun would shoot a massive a massive steel oblong projectile of 144 kg as well as an oblong grenade of 100 kg and a round explosive bullet of 48 kg.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In a work printed in 1867, the 24 cm modèle 1864 gun was said to be 4.56 m long, to have a diameter of 0.98 m at the breech, and to weigh 14,000 kg.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The weight of the gun was later said to be 14,500 kg instead of 14,000 kg.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The weight given in 1867 might seem to originate from a rounding decision.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] There is however a compelling reason to assume that the early model indeed weighed only 14,000 kg.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The same publication that noted the weight as 14,000 kg also published an image of the gun.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This image shows that for this early model, the part of the barrel behind the trunnions had a bigger diameter than that at the trunnions.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Later drawings show the diameter to be the same at the trunnions and just behind the trunnions.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] At the Paris Exposition Universelle (1867), two of the modèle 1864 guns were shown.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] One of the drawings published on account of the exhibition shows an early model of the barrel of the 24 cm modèle 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Another exhibitor at the fair was the company Compagnie des Hauts-fourneaux, forges et aciéries de la Marine et des chemins de fer, commonly known as Petin and Gaudet.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This made the steel rings for the M 1864 guns and had supplied such rings to: Italy, Spain, England, Denmark, Russia, Turkey, and Norway.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The 'Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 Transformé au modèle 1870' was a Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 transformed to be like the Canon de 24 C modèle 1870.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The primary change consisted of boring up the barrel and introducing a steel inner tube through the muzzle.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This inner tube ran the entire length of bore of the barrel, instead of being shorter like that of the M 70.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This operation could only be done after first heating up the barrel to remove the existing rings.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This relieved the stress on the barrel, making it possible to insert the inner tube, which of course came under stress after the barrel cooled down.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] After the gun had been 'tubed', the rings could then be placed back, making it all quite costly.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The length of the powder chamber of the Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 T 70 was increased, meaning that the length of the barrel that could be used to accelerate the projectile decreased.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The use of a higher charge of (slower burning) gunpowder nevertheless allowed the projectiles to attain higher velocities without leading to higher peak pressures.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The other changes were inside the inner tube, which got the same rifling as the M 1870.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The obturation and ignition were also the same, which necessitated a change to the breech piece.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] All these changes allowed the 24 C modèle 1864 T 70 to use the same charges and projectiles as the M 70.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The barrel of the 24 cm modèle 1864 was 4,560 mm long.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It was made of cast iron hooped with steel rings.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Early designs were for a barrel with either a breech *à coin* or a screw (*à vis*) breech.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In the end, the barrels with an à coin breech were not put into service and were modified.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The length of bore of the barrel was 4,197 mm.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] There were many changes to the dimensions of the rifled part, the transitional cone and the chamber.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In the final June 1868 design, the length of the 'partie cylindrique' (rifled part?) of the barrel was 3,511.5 mm.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The dimensions of the powder chamber were then set at 645 by 252.8 mm, but in the end it was 651 mm long.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] There was a 25 mm long transitional cone.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The place for the obturator was 33 mm long.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In the final design, the length of the place were the breech set was 277.5 mm long.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Ignition of the charge took place via a traditional hold drilled towards the chamber at 500 mm before the breech.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] There were five grooves, which were also changed on multiple occasions.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Groove number 1 was a bit different from the other ones.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The inner configuration of the Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 T 70 was the same as that of the Canon de 24 C modèle 1870.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The details of the system of ringing / hooping the gun are interesting in order to distinguish between early and late models of the gun.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Early designs called for a single or a double layer of rings.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Two systems of single layer hooping were applied.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In September 1866, the double layer of rings became mandatory, but this also had variations.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The December 1864 double layer system had 11 rings in the first layer and six in the second.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The September 1866 system of two layers of rings was widely applied.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The part of the barrel where the rings were applied had a diameter of 720 mm.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] On the first layer, the September 1866 system had (from the breech side), a breech ring that was 125 mm thick and covered the next ring for a length of 100 mm.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Next came four rings of 250 mm length and 60 mm thickness.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] These were followed by a ring that was tronconic in front and was cut in over a length of 100 mm to give support to the last ring of the second layer.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The trunnion ring came next and was 300 mm long and 107 mm thick.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In front of this came an unspecified ring that was before the trunnion ring.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In January 1867, this design was changed by placing two rings below a thinner trunnion ring.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The layers of rings of these designs were all 1.98 m long and 125 mm thick.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The above engraving published about the gun as shown at the 1867 Paris World's Fair has very strong similarities to this description.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It might also apply to the surviving La Valérie canon.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The final configuration called for two layers of the rings and was determined in February 1867.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This final system had 8 rings in both layers.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The first layer was 2,000 mm long, the second was 1,817 mm long.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The first layer had 8 rings of 250 mm length.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The seven nearest the breech were 65 mm thick.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The one near the muzzle had a tronconic side to make the transition to the barrel and had a shoulder for the first ring of the second layer.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The total diameter of the barrel near the breech was therefore 720 + (2*(65 + 60)) = 970 mm.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] At its thickest, the diameter was 990 mm.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This description matches the image 'M 1864-66 and M 1870'.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] There were multiple kinds of projectiles for the 24 cm modèle 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] There was a regular cast iron grenade; a chilled cast iron armor-piercing grenade; a steel armor-piercing grenade; cast iron exercise grenades and canister shot.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] These all had two rows of five studs that guided the projectile through the barrel to give it rotation.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In general, the weight of the projectiles was twice that of the solid round cast iron shot for the caliber.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The weight of the charge was between 1/6 and 1/7th of the weight of the projectile.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The regular grenade of cast iron was called *obus oblong en fonte* literally meaning 'long grenade of cast iron'.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It was about 2.25 times as long as its diameter, i.e.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Of this, the ogive part was between 1 and 1.25 calibers long.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This grenade weighed 100 kg, of which the explosive charge was 4.676 kg.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The chilled cast iron armor piercing grenade *obus oblong en fonte dure* was about L/2.5 long.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This grenade weighed 144 kg, of which the explosive charge weighed 1.850 kg.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The *boulet ogival en acier* was a steel armor-piercing shot.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The earliest steel shot were either ogive (called ogivo-cylindrique) or cylindrical.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The cylindrical steel shot were intended for use on the shortest ranges, the ogive ones for somewhat longer ranges.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] After September 1868, the cylindrical projectiles were changed to become ogive.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The ogival cast iron exercise shot was about L/2.5 long.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It was modeled on the steel shot, but was longer to compensate for the lower density of cast iron.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 T 70 used the projectiles of the Canon de 24 C modèle 1870.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The velocity at which an armor-piercing projectile left the barrel of the gun was crucial for its ability to penetrate armor.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In general, a higher (propellant) charge meant a higher velocity, but also a higher peak pressure.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Changing the construction of the gun could make it more resilient to these pressures.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In 1867, the charge used for the armor-piercing shot was given as 20 kg.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In the early 1880s, the charge for the armor piercing shot (*projectile de rupture*) was given as 24 kg.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] With this charge a velocity of 340 m/s was attained.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] 70, the charge for the armor piercing grenade was given as 41.5 kg and velocity was 480 m/s.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The regular grenade was fired with lower charges.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In 1867 and in the early 1880s, this was 16 kg.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This did not mean that velocity was not important.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] At the maximum range of about 8 km, the flight of the projectile took about 45 seconds, during which the wind would blow it off course.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] However, while working with pressures closer to the maximum, the actual pressure in the gun was less predictable.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] When the gun was changed to become the 24 C modèle 1864 T.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] 70, it used a charge of 37 kg of slower burning gunpowder, which gave a 120 kg regular grenade the same velocity as the armor-piercing shot, i.e.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The ballistic tables of the 24 cm gun gave its ranges for the different projectiles, charges and elevations.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] With a charge of 24 kg, the armor-piercing massive ogive shot had an effective range of 1,400 m.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] With the 20 kg charge, this was only 1,000 m.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The ogive exercise shot was fired with 16 kg, and therefore got no further than 600 m.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] For the armor-piercing cylindrical projectile the ranges with 24 kg and 20 kg were also 1,400 and 1,000 m.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The regular grenade did not have to pierce armor by its mechanical impact.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It could therefore be fired at a higher elevation, relying on the explosive charge of the grenade to damage the target.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] With a charge of 16 kg and at an elevation of 37.5°, the grenade (*obus oblong*) could be used to hit targets at a distance of 8,000 m.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] However, the maximum elevation of the naval 'battery' carriages (below) was probably no more than 11 degrees.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] At that elevation, the maxium range was only 4,000 m.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] There were two kinds of gun deck or battery deck naval carriages: the modèle 1864 and the modèle 1867.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] With some changes (improved brakes), both could also be used for the Canon de 24 C modèle 1870.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] These carriages consisted of an upper carriage that recoiled backwards over a frame (châssis) called slide.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] During this movement a compressor brake caught the recoil.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] These carriages were meant to be used on the battery deck of a ship and therefore had only limited elevation.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 is also well known as a coastal gun.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] For this role, multiple carriages were available.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The affût de côte a pivot a l'avant pour canons de 24 cent. was a carriage that consisted of a wooden upper carriage and a cast iron slide.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] At its front, the slide was attached to a pivot, which kept the slide in place and allowed it to turn on semi-circular rails.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The whole was placed on a platform of masonry placed behind an earthen breastwork.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The affût de côte a pivot central pour canons de 24 cent. was made for situations that required a large horizontal arc of fire.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] As its name implies, the carriage revolved around a central pivot and thus on circular rails.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 T 70 used the same carriages as the Canon de 24 C modèle 1870.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In December 1867, the Dutch government appointed a commission to investigate the possibilities to quickly acquire heavy coastal guns.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In March 1868, this commission advised to buy six Canon de 24 C modèle 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It advised to have the barrels cast by the Finspång Ironworks.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The rings should be made by the Compagnie des Hauts-fourneaux, forges et aciéries de la Marine et des chemins de fer in Rive-de-Gier.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The breech should be made by Varral, Elwell & Poulot in Paris, and the whole should be assembled in Sweden.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] This advice led to dozens of 24 C modèle 1864 getting made for the Dutch army.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In 1872, the Dutch government planned to have 89 guns of 24 cm caliber.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Of these 52 would be used in the Fortifications of Den Helder to protect the naval base there.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] To protect the accesses to Rotterdam, 4 guns would be placed in Brielle; 13 in Hellevoetsluis; and 20 in Willemstad, North Brabant.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In the end, not all of these guns would be 24 cm ijzer.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The Gloire-class ironclads were initially armed with 36 16 cm modèle 1858-60 guns.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In 1869, Gloire's 34 battery deck guns were replaced by six Canon de 24 C modèle 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] There were three on each side, mounted on the carriage with iron frame model 1867.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The Magenta-class ironclads *Magenta* and *Solférino* were also initially armed with smoothbore guns.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In 1866 *Solférino* got ten Canon de 24 C modèle 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] When *Magenta* sank, she had ten 24 cm M 1864 guns on the battery deck.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The Provence-class ironclads were also planned to get smoothbore guns.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] However, by the time they were nearing completion, this changed.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] By then, *Flandre* was planned to get a mixed armament of twenty 50-pounder smoothbore guns and ten 16 cm rifled guns.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] Later, this became eight Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 on the battery deck and four 19 cm breechloaders higher up.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The other nine ships of the class underwent the same changes to their armament as *Flandre*.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] After France bought USS Dunderberg and renamed her to *Rochambeau*, she was rearmed.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] She got four Canon de 27 C modèle 1864 and ten Canon de 24 C modèle 1864.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The United States monitor Onondaga was re-armed with four Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 after she was acquired by France in May 1867.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] On land, the Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 was of course used to arm a number of coastal defense batteries.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] However, the gun was also used in land battles during the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The 'La Valérie canon' is an object classed as movable cultural heritage.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It was used during the Siege of Paris (1870–1871), taken to Berlin as a trophy in 1871, brought to Paris after World War I, moved back to Berlin in 1940 and brought to the French Army Museum at Les Invalides in 1947.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In 1989 it was re-installed at Fort Mont-Valérien.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In 2004 a Canon de 24 C modèle 1864 was found in Papeete, capital of French Polynesia.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It has since been mounted on a concrete base.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] The 24 cm ijzer in the Nationaal Militair Museum of the Netherlands was originally placed at Willemstad.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It was damaged when the previous artillery museum at Doorwerth Castle came under fire during the 1944 Operation Market Garden.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] In July 2007 one of the 24 ijzer guns of Hellevoetsluis was unearthed at the beach.
[src:canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864/canon-de-24-c-modèle-1864] It has since been mounted at the fortress on a reconstructed carriage.
